article.description:
LaToya Thomas scored all 21 of her points in
the second half Friday night, helping the San Antonio Silver Stars
beat the Indiana Fever 82-65.
article.headline: Thomas comes alive in second half
article.linkText: Fever get dose of harsh medicine from Stars
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- LaToya Thomas scored all 21 of her points in
the second half Friday night, helping the San Antonio Silver Stars
beat the Indiana Fever 82-65.

Five San Antonio players finished in double figures and the
Silver Stars shot 59 percent from the field, the best shooting
performance in the league this season. Adrienne Goodson had 16
points, and Shannon Johnson, Semeka Randeall and Adrian Williams
added 10 apiece.

Thomas sat out most of the first half after picking up two quick
fouls. She made up for her absence in the second half, shooting
8-for-9.

"She can knock the shots down. We didn't realize how open she
was and she just let it go," said San Antonio coach Shelly Dailey.
"I didn't tell her anything. That's just the way LaToya plays. The
last couple of games she has been shooting the lights out."

The winning margin was the largest in franchise history for San
Antonio, which won consecutive games for just the second time this
season. It was the Silver Stars' third road win in 16 games.

"We're not going anywhere (this season), but in our hearts and
minds we're going somewhere in the future and we're preparing for
that," Dailey said.

Indiana's Tamika Catchings, who sustained a toe injury in
practice Monday, had her streak of 96 consecutive starts snapped.
She played just 13 minutes and finished with five points and four
rebounds.

"We were surprised that Tamika wasn't out there. We figured she
is such a competitor that even if she's injured she plays," Dailey
said. "We just wanted to play solid defense and that was the
game."

San Antonio enjoyed a huge advantage at the free-throw line,
shooting 29-of-37. Indiana went 3-for-5.

"We didn't do a very good job of going inside. We were very
tentative attacking their height inside," said Kelly Miller, who
led Indiana with 17 points, including a career-high five
3-pointers.

San Antonio center Margo Dydek game Indiana plenty of trouble
inside. The 7-foot-2 Dydek had four blocked shots, seven points,
seven assists and six rebounds.

"Margo was a definite factor," said Indiana coach Brian
Winters, who had hoped to rest Catchings the entire game. "We did
miss her starting. She is day-to-day with the turf toe. It is never
a good injury."

Kelly Schumacher added 15 for the Fever, who shot 34 percent.

The loss was costly for Indiana in the tight Eastern Conference
playoff race. The Fever (15-16) fell out of a tie for first place
in the East and dropped to third, a half-game behind Charlotte and
Connecticut (15-15) with three games to play.

Catchings sat out the entire first half, and the Fever faced a
33-24 deficit at the break.

Indiana, which had its season-best three-game winning streak
ended, never seriously challenged in the second half.
